@stevemyopinion423 Everyone has a right to their opinion, but I feel so gaslit when people say they like the Snyder cut better. I found it INSUFFERABLE. I mean Snyder opens with like a 2 and half minute scene of Superman yelling followed. Then that's followed by a 15 minute Amzonian fight scene, because that makes sense in a film called the Justice League. 

Never mind the fact that Wonder Woman is blowing out the sides of a building murdering people rather than subduing them and winking at small girls that they too can be a killer if they just believe in themselves. Or the fact that Flash can slow motion perv on a random woman, after she is just so infatuated by the Flash she's partially responsible for a car crash (mind you the SECOND woman who can't drive in the movie, hello Cyborg's mom) with phallic hot dogs flying at her face. Or how Darkseid just forgot where Earth was even though he had fought on the planet. Or how Cyborg, a genius, has the most generic 90s daddy issues of he didn't come to my football game. That's a backstory that I'm supposed to care about? 

Whedon's version had some cringey jokes (but also some good ones), and a badly acted and bloated/drunk Affleck, but it was way more economical, and characters made sense.

@FlorisDVijfde She worked with her dad her whole childhood, grew up in a shipyard. She probably had parts in her hands to play with before she could crawl. In the time she meets Reynolds at her fathers enterprise she is a minimum of 20, meaning she has had around 20 years soaking up how and on what mechanics work and probably at least ten, maybe fifteen years working machines progressively by herself. (In that environment, people who weren't rich learned their trades from their parents and had no or nearly no formal education beyond learning to write and do theirs sums.)  
It's the background that comes in bits and pieces and the obvious analogy to the "Wild West" throughout the show. She is a fully fleshed out character. 
Back then, they just expected the audience to listen, watch and think instead of just consuming.

@shawnsmith2006 Her powers were strictly tied to her being an empath. Not a super soldier. She was able to read minds. Which is quite powerful in and of itself. As in she could predict where they were going to fire their guns. Nothing about her power set, as set up by the series, suggested she could take on hoards of reavers (who aren't thinking beings). 

Realistically given how her powers worked the very presence of Reavers should have debilitated her.

It felt unnecessary, even in the show where Walsh and Mal were being rescued.
